    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:66aa0131-08b1-4ee8-ab35-ec9e33a44e57",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 53-year-old woman with a medium build and slightly rounded posture, a common adaptation to chronic low back discomfort she has carried for years. She presents to the clinic today moving cautiously, favouring her right side and grimacing mildly when transitioning from sitting to standing. She is neatly dressed in comfortable, loose-fitting clothes and supportive walking shoes — a practical wardrobe choice she adopted after her pain worsened.\n\n{patientName} works as an elementary school librarian, a job she genuinely loves but that demands long hours on her feet, frequent bending to shelve books, and carrying moderately heavy boxes of new arrivals. She describes her typical workday as \"eight hours of my back arguing with me.\" At home she lives with her husband of 27 years and their teenage daughter; her older son recently moved out for university. She manages most household chores herself and finds vacuuming and grocery shopping particularly aggravating to her symptoms.\n\nHer pain is primarily located in the lumbosacral region, rated 6–7 out of 10 on most days, described as a dull, aching pressure that radiates into the left buttock and down the posterior left thigh — consistent with sciatic nerve irritation — though it does not extend below the knee. On palpation, there is notable paraspinal muscle tenderness at the L4–L5 and L5–S1 levels bilaterally, and she winces on direct pressure over the left sacroiliac region. Morning stiffness lasting 30–40 minutes is a daily complaint. She notes that prolonged sitting and forward bending worsen the pain, while lying down with a pillow under her knees provides partial relief. She has tried heat pads and over-the-counter ibuprofen with inconsistent benefit.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} used to enjoy gardening and light hiking with her husband, but has significantly curtailed these activities over the past 18 months due to pain. She recently joined a gentle yoga class on her physiotherapist's advice and reports modest improvement in flexibility. She is an avid reader and enjoys cooking elaborate weekend meals for family and friends. Socially active, she is part of a neighbourhood book club that meets monthly.\n\n{patientName} appears mildly anxious about her condition, expressing concern that her pain might be \"something serious.\" She denies any bowel or bladder dysfunction, fever, unexplained weight loss, or night sweats. Neurological symptoms such as foot drop or frank weakness are absent. She is motivated to recover and asks thoughtful questions about her treatment plan, indicating a strong understanding of her condition and high health literacy."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
